<br>
The OSP is no longer an orbiting space station like the shuttle, which is good, because we have the ISS.  With a 7 man crew, we can get real science out of the ISS, and get shorter missions out of our OSP.  We don't need an overblown RLV, just a crew taxi to get us to the ISS.<br>
<br>
The minimum requirement is a 4 man crew.  I've heard from somebody who works on the shuttle that they would really prefer a 7 man vehicle, but they want to give a minimum requirement to see what they get.  <br>
<br>
You're factoring a huge number of costs that simply aren't there.  The OSP will be a small RLV, with room for the supplies of the crew.  There won't be cargo costs, no science equipment costs, just the costs of the booster and the costs of the shuttle itself.  <br>
<br>
I am very happy with NASA's approach to the OSP.  It will save tremendous amounts of money, especially if we start mass producing them (20-50) and the boosters.  <br>
<br>
And after the Columbia incident, I wouldn't be surprised to see them fly in 5-10 years.  And I also wouldn't be surprised to see them fly after the next generation spacecraft comes out, too.  The next shuttle can be designed as payload, to supplement this shuttle.<br>
